To control what gets loaded by Hibernate Search, you can leverage [JPA entity graphs in Hibernate Search](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/stable/search/reference/en-US/html_single/#search-dsl-query-entity-graph) by calling `.loading( o -&gt; o.graph( someGraph, GraphSemantic.FETCH ) )` when building your search query.

Something like this?

```
public List&lt;Tobacco&gt; find(String query) {
    EntityGraph&lt;Tobacco&gt; graph = entityManager.createEntityGraph( Tobacco.class ); 
    graph.addAttributeNodes( &quot;manufacturer&quot; );
    graph.addAttributeNodes( &quot;flavors&quot; );
    return Search.session(entityManager)
        .search(Tobacco.class)
        .where(f -&gt; f.match()
            .fields(&quot;barcode&quot;, &quot;name&quot;).boost(2.0f)
            .fields(&quot;name_prefix&quot;)
            .matching(query)
            .fuzzy()
        )
        .loading( o -&gt; o.graph( graph, GraphSemantic.FETCH ) ) 
        .fetchHits(10);
}
```

However, depending on your model and entity graph, this might lead to more than one query being executed regardless (due to implementation constraints in Hibernate ORM). In that case, you can explore these alternative solutions that will affect any loading, not just loading in Hibernate Search:

* Use [`@Fetch(FetchMode.JOIN)`](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/5.6/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#fetching-fetchmode-join) on your `flavors` association.
* Leverage Hibernate ORM’s batch fetching to only ever trigger two SQL queries (one for the tobacco instances, one for their flavors): see the [`batch_fetch_size` configuration property](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/5.6/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#configurations-database-fetch) and the [`@BatchSize` annotation](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/orm/5.6/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#fetching-batch).

